SIMPLE: stable
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stable
<hw>Sta"ble</hw> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧"b'l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>estable</ets>, F. <ets>stable</ets>, fr. L. <ets>stabilis</ets>,
fr. <ets>stare</ets> to stand. See <er>Stand</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos> and
cf. <er>Establish</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Firmly established; not
easily moved, shaken, or overthrown; fixed; <as>as, a <ex>stable</ex>
government</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In this region of chance, . . . where nothing is
<qex>stable</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Rogers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Steady in purpose; constant; firm in resolution; not
easily diverted from a purpose; not fickle or wavering; <as>as, a man of
<ex>stable</ex> character</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And to her husband ever meek and <qex>stable</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Durable; not subject to overthrow or change; firm;
<as>as, a <ex>stable</ex> foundation; a <ex>stable</ex>
position.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>So placed as to resist forces
tending to cause motion; of such structure as to resist distortion or
molecular or chemical disturbance; -- said of any body or
substance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stable equilibrium</b></col> <fld>(Mech.)</fld>, <cd>the
kind of equilibrium of a body so placed that if disturbed it returns to
its former position, as in the case when the center of gravity is below
the point or axis of support; -- opposed to <contr>unstable
equilibrium</contr>, in which the body if disturbed does not tend to
return to its former position, but to move farther away from it, as in
the case of a body supported at a point below the center of gravity. Cf.
<cref>Neutral equilibrium</cref>, under <er>Neutral</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Fixed; steady; constant; abiding; strong;
durable; firm.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stable</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stable
<hw>Sta"ble</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To fix; to establish.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stable</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stable
<hw>Sta"ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>estable</ets>, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧table</ets>, from L. <ets>stabulum</ets>, fr.
<ets>stare</ets> to stand. See <er>Stand</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety>
<def>A house, shed, or building, for beasts to lodge and feed in; esp.,
a building or apartment with stalls, for horses; <as>as, a horse
<ex>stable</ex>; a cow <ex>stable</ex>.</as></def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stable fly</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a common
dipterous fly (<spn>Stomoxys calcitrans</spn>) which is abundant about
stables and often enters dwellings, especially in autumn; called also
<altname>biting house fly</altname>. These flies, unlike the common
house flies, which they resemble, bite severely, and are troublesome to
horses and cattle. They differ from the larger <er>horse
fly</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stable</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Stable
<hw>Sta"ble</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Stabled</conjf> <pr>(-b'ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stabling</conjf> <pr>(-bl⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To put or
keep in a stable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stable</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Stable
<hw>Sta"ble</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To dwell or lodge in a stable;
to dwell in an inclosed place; to kennel.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stableman</ent>⟦br⟧
